@node "install" "Installation and Usage"

@{u}@{b}Hardware requirements@{ub}@{uu}

An AmigaOS 4 system is required.

@{u}@{b}Software requirements@{ub}@{uu}

atheros5000.device needs AmigaOS 4.0 or greater.

@{u}@{b}Installation@{ub}@{uu}

To install atheros5000.device, run the 'Install' script. In your networking
software, set the SANA-II device name to @{b}networks/atheros5000.device@{ub} and
the unit number to @{b}0@{ub}.

This package includes a utility called WirelessManager that runs in the
background and sets up connections to wireless networks. It is necessary to
start WirelessManager from the S:Startup-Sequence script to ensure that a
wireless connection is established before the TCP/IP stack starts its DHCP
client. Since this cannot be easily done by the install script, the
following line should be manually inserted just before AddNetInterface or
Network-Startup is called:

    Run <>NIL: C:WirelessManager atheros5000.device

@{u}@{b}Wireless parameters@{ub}@{uu}

Parameters for your wireless networks are specified in the file
'ENVARC:Sys/Wireless.prefs'. You can choose to have this file created
automatically while running the 'Install' script. The installer lets you
create a configuration for a single WPA/WPA2-encrypted network. If you need
other options, or want to configure more than one network, you will need to
edit 'ENVARC:Sys/Wireless.prefs' in a text editor. Below are some examples
of network configurations that can be used.


# A WPA/WPA2-encrypted network with a textual passphrase
# (using a textual WPA passphrase may cause a start-up delay of up to
# several seconds)

network={
	ssid="mynet1"
	psk="yOuRsEcRetwpAKeY"
}

# A WPA/WPA2-encrypted network with a hexadecimal key
# (note that the key will need to be recalculated if the SSID is changed)

network={
	ssid="mynet1"
	psk=b368b34a7ba4051bea1f9aed30a179d4e56ae1c8624c1fabd2f5f0f7c0db12a3
}

# A WEP-encrypted network with a hexadecimal key

network={
	ssid="mynet2"
	key_mgmt=NONE
	wep_key0=123456789abcdef123456789ab
	wep_tx_keyidx=0
}

# A WEP-encrypted network with a textual password

network={
	ssid="mynet3"
	key_mgmt=NONE
	wep_key0="yourpassword1"
	wep_tx_keyidx=0
}

# Match any unencrypted network

network={
	key_mgmt=NONE
}

